# Technical Formatting

Sources: Microsoft Writing Style Guide, Elastic Docs Style Guide

## Spelling and Language

- Use **American English** consistently. No British variants.
  - "optimization" not "optimisation"
  - "color" not "colour"
  - "behavior" not "behaviour"

## Headings

- Use **sentence case** for all headings: capitalize only the first word and proper nouns.
  - "Configure the DMA pipeline" not "Configure The DMA Pipeline"
- Headings must be descriptive — a reader scanning headings alone should understand the page structure.

## Code Elements in Prose

| Element | Format | Example |
|---------|--------|---------|
| Class / struct names | backtick code | `TiledMma`, `SharedMemory` |
| Function / method names | backtick code with `()` | `make_tiled_copy()`, `partition()` |
| Variable names | backtick code | `tile_size`, `smem_buf` |
| File names | backtick code | `matmul.cu`, `Makefile` |
| CLI commands | backtick code | `nvcc -o kernel kernel.cu` |
| Keyword / language constructs | backtick code | `__global__`, `template` |
| New domain terms (first use) | **bold** on first use, then plain | **Warp Specialization** |
| UI elements | **bold** | **Settings > Build** |

## Lists

- Use **numbered lists** for sequential steps.
- Use **bulleted lists** for unordered items.
- Every list must have **at least 2 items**.
- Maintain **parallel grammatical structure** within a list.

```markdown
<!-- BAD (not parallel) -->
- Configure the tile size
- The DMA pipeline should be set up
- Running the kernel

<!-- GOOD (parallel: all imperative) -->
- Configure the tile size
- Set up the DMA pipeline
- Run the kernel
```

## Numbers

- Spell out one through nine in prose. Use numerals for 10 and above.
- Always use numerals for measurements, versions, and performance data: "4 KB", "SM90", "1.2 TFLOPS".
